ions. But will our grandchildren's grandchildren enjoy the cornucopian bounty most of us take for granted? This first history of the future to put food at the center of the story provides an intriguing perspective on this question for anyone—from general readers to policy analysts, historians, and students of the future—who has wondered about the future of life's most basic requirement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFood supply. 0aFoodxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  a20th century american culture.  a20th century american food history.  aamerican studies.  acooking.  aculinary.  adisney amusements parks.  adisney world.  adisneyland.  adystopia.  afarmers markets.  afood and innovation.  afood and technology.  afood security.  afood supply.  afood writings.  afood.  afuture of food.  afuturistic films.  afuturistic novels.  agastronomy.  agenetic engineering.  agmos.  ahuman anxiety.  ahumanity.  aorganic foods.  arestaurants.  asocial anxiety.  asupermarkets.  autopia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025035240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094046840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940468/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY